{
  "texts": [
    "Although the number of parameters in the considered architectures is larger than the size of the training sets, they exhibit a logarithmic scaling with the number of qubits.",
    "Meanwhile, the number of dimensions of the quantum states scales exponentially.",
    "Hence, it is inappropriate to categorize the models we have investigated as large in the same way as the classical models in ref. 62.",
    "We find the ability of small quantum learning models to fit random data as unexpected, as witnessed by the many works on uniform generalization bounds for quantum models published during the aftermath of ref. 62.",
    "This observation reveals a promising research direction: not only must we rethink our approach to studying generalization in QML, but we must also recognize that the mechanisms leading to successful generalization in QML may differ entirely from those in classical machine learning."
  ]
}